<font color="#FF0000">TO KALI TAL</font><br>
<tt>Thu May  1 21:14:45 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Kali Tal:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;It was not my intent that my private email be posted to the POV list. Forwarding of private mail without permission of the author is unethical, and, arguably, illegal. The reason I did not want the message forwarded was *not* because I didn't want to stand behind my words, but because I did not want to be drawn into exactly this sort of pointless and ill-advised discussion.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
You have been on the internet long enough to realize that NOTHING is private and secure. If you do not want the world to read it, don't write it. Use snail mail. From an ethics standpoint, the appearance of a divergence from overt philosophy is newsworthy, especially in a forum dedicated to the disection and debate of thorny issues. Doc Spatz, as I have posted earlier, was operating entirely within an ethical framework such as employed by members of the press.<br>
A public figure such as yourself is well advised to keep that in mind at all times. As far as being drawn into this discussion, voila!, you are HERE! <br><br>
&gt;&quot;I am politically progressive. I am a feminist. I am an anti-racist. I make no bones about that. As such, I run a journal, a press, a conference, and a web site which are hospitable to my values. If others don't like my politics or my attitude, I frankly don't give a damn.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
It is my opinion that you appear as an honest person with these remarks. This site, however, seems to be populated with individuals whose views are more cosmipolitan and are driven by a thirst for knowledge and what they perceive as a truth. It is my experience that free discussion from all sides allows a greater opportunity for explorations in understanding in a cross cultural sense where personal bias, bigotry, proclivity, and anti-somethingorothers are put aside or hotly debated. It is the process that engenders greater understanding of other views and fosters sensitivity and respect in relationships with others. Surely your positions on feminism and anti-racism have their historical roots in such constructive processes. Why, then, criticize the process here or go to length to convey an attitude of self proclaimed exclusivity? It is my opinion that we have a non-sequitur here. Do you agree? <br><br>
&gt;&quot;But the charge that I am &quot;anti-veteran&quot; is beyond laughable. It is a common tactic for right-wing veterans to dismiss my work because it doesn't represent &quot;the veteran's viewpoint.&quot; Of course, by that they mean *their* view<br>
point.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Speaking of &quot;common tactics&quot;, I feel the statement above is not consistent with your philosophy described by the one previous. If you do not &quot;give a damn&quot; for the views of others, how can you complain when others find exception to your views? I would think that you would welcome the intellectual challenge of debate in the classic sense to either prove your points, or learn about the views of others. To do less seems to me to be an abandonment of the noble and open minded intellectual principles of academic persuit of the truth for the betterment of humanity. After all, isn't that what the process is all about? Most centers of higher learning have architecture that reflects upon classic traditions of learning. Your comments do not spawn such complimentary images in my mind, and in my opinion.<br><br>
It is my opinion that you are not &quot;anti-veteran&quot; in a true sense, but rather<br>
 &quot;anti-everything-that-does-not-agree-with-my opinion&quot;.<br><br>
That opinion of mine is drawn from my application of classic logical sylogism from the comments you have posted on this site.<br><br>
Have a nice day.    
<p><code>-- art16@ix.netcom.com  (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


